  "result": "No code changes were made. Build remains green (0 errors).\n\n**Report:**\n\n**Root cause:** The test fails at line 102 of gengc.lua: `assert(f() == 123 and ...)`. By bisecting, I confirmed `f` is bound to a **string**, not a function. The string comes from `aux_resume` in `crates/lua-stdlib/src/coro_lib.rs:113`, which pushes `\"coroutines not yet implemented (Phase E)\"` and returns `-1`. `co_resume` then packages this as `(false, \"...\")` — valid Lua semantics for resume failure. The test does `local _, f = coroutine.resume(co)` without checking the success boolean, so `f` becomes the error string; calling `f()` later produces `\"attempt to call a string value\"`.\n\n**This is not a Phase-B bug to fix.** Per PORTING.md §2 #6, coroutines are intentionally stubbed in Phases A–D and require corosensei stackful-coroutine integration in Phase E. `LuaThread` is still a placeholder unit type (`crates/lua-types/src/value.rs:323-327`). Making the test pass requires implementing real coroutines — well out of scope for a single debug invocation.\n\n**Fix:** None applied. The harness misclassified this as `runtime-error` because the stub deliberately *emulates* C's auxresume error path (rather than panicking) so pcall-aware callers can continue. gengc.lua doesn't pcall the resume, so it falls into a misleading downstream error. The test cannot pass until Phase E lands.\n\n**New state:** Test still fails identically — no changes made. Build green.",
